7. Reflections
•	Running tests FIRST, before making any changes, surfaced a real pre-existing bug that documentation alone wouldn't have revealed
•	Documenting the final-year contribution exclusion forced careful reading of the logic — and that reading is what led to discovering the bug
•	Parameter names and internal variable names need different levels of caution — public signatures used in tests are riskier to rename
•	Good documentation doesn't just describe code — it can also surface assumptions that turn out to be questionable, like the time - 1 logic
•	Writing the Note: section in the docstring about the business rule was the single most valuable addition — without it, future developers would assume the time-1 behavior is a bug and might 'fix' it incorrectly

